                <h2>Fundamental Components of Financial Literacy</h2>
                <p>Financial literacy is essential for achieving long-term financial well-being. It encompasses various components that empower individuals to make informed decisions about their money. These include:</p>

                <h3>1. Budgeting</h3>
                <p>Budgeting involves planning how to allocate your income across different uses, such as spending, investing, saving, and giving. A well-balanced budget ensures financial security and prosperity by prioritizing essential needs, paying off existing debts, and setting aside money for future goals. Effective budgeting allows individuals to live within their means while working toward financial stability.</p>

                <h3>2. Investing</h3>
                <p>Investing is about growing your wealth by putting money into opportunities that yield returns over time. To become financially literate in investing, it's important to understand key concepts such as interest rates, price levels, diversification, risk mitigation, and market indexes. By mastering these fundamentals, individuals can make smarter investment choices, mitigate risks, and maximize their income potential.</p>

                <h3>3. Borrowing</h3>
                <p>Borrowing is a common financial activity, but it needs to be done wisely. Understanding interest rates, compound interest, the time value of money, payment periods, and loan structures is crucial for effective borrowing. When these aspects are clear, individuals can minimize borrowing costs, manage repayments, and reduce long-term financial stress, ensuring better financial health.</p>

                <h3>4. Taxation</h3>
                <p>Taxation significantly affects net income, making it an important aspect of financial literacy. Different income sources—such as employment, investments, rentals, and inheritances—are taxed differently. Gaining knowledge about various tax rates and deductions helps individuals optimize their income, plan for tax obligations, and achieve economic stability.</p>

                <h3>5. Personal Financial Management</h3>
                <p>At the core of financial literacy is personal financial management, which involves integrating all the above components. By balancing budgeting, investing, borrowing, and taxation, individuals can create a comprehensive financial plan. This approach helps in building savings, increasing investments, and reducing debts, ultimately leading to financial security and independence.</p>

                <p>Mastering these fundamental components of financial literacy equips individuals with the skills needed to navigate financial challenges, make sound decisions, and secure a prosperous future.</p>
            </div>
        </section>


